<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,1303,2014]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,1663,1689]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Habitat.</emphasis>
This species was found abundant in all of our surveys. It was mostly found in the intertidal during low tides, between rocks and crevices and occasionally in tide pools, and in high energy wave areas. Juvenile specimens were found at 
<quantity box="[312,383,1735,1762]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="471" unit="m" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5 m</quantity>
depth on small rocks buried in sand.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="472" pageId="20" pageNumber="471" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,1303,2014]" lastBlockId="21.[151,1437,151,646]" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="472" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1771,1797]" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Remarks.</emphasis>
Examination of specimens from Oaxaca (Puerto Ángel, Estacahuite, Salina Cruz), Guerrero (Costa Chica, Acapulco, Costa Grande) and Mazatlán (Playa Norte, Playa Faro, 
<collectingCountry box="[991,1031,1807,1833]" name="Iceland" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Isla</collectingCountry>
Venados) revealed an unique color pattern for specimens from each region. We identified that the specimens from Oaxaca display a mostly light to dark olive-green tegmentum, while tegmentum color of specimens from Guerrero showed a variety of, vary from red to brown, and from dark to lighter green. Specimens from Sayulita, Nayarit (e.g., CNMO 40012) are mostly olivegreen with irregular dark lines (6–9), arranged longitudinally along the diagonal ridge and on the posterior margin of intermediate valves which show a “zebra” like pattern (
<figureCitation box="[776,892,1987,2013]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1746,1770]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-18@35.[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 20. Chiton articulatus, specimen BL 27 mm, El Faro, Mazatlán (CNMO 5661); shows the tegmentum color details A, head valve; B, intermediate valves III-V; C, tail valve. Specimen BL 24.45 mm, Santa Elena, Oaxaca (CNMO 1066); shows color tegmentum details; D, head valve; E, detail of intermediate valves III-V; F, tail valve. Chaetopleura lurida, G, dorsal view of whole specimen BL 21.3 x 13.7 mm, Estacahuite, Oaxaca (CNMO 5813). Chaetopleura lurida, specimen of 27.9 x 15.4 mm, dorsal view of valve I and IV, Isla Partida, Baja California Sur (CNMO 1004), H, head valve and I, valve IV; J, whole specimen BL 25.8 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit; K, Ischnochiton muscarius, whole specimen BL 27.6 mm in dorsal view.Callistochiton elenensis, L, whole specimen BL 19.46 mm, La Paz, Baja California Sur (UAGRO 0060); M, detail of sculpturing of valves II-IV; N, Chiton articulatus, N, whole specimen in dorsal view, BL 37.2 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit (CNMO 40012)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691308" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691308/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="471">Figs. 20N</figureCitation>
). Specimens from Mazatlán exhibit radial bands (to the valve apex) of purple or dark red color, which turn brown 
<emphasis box="[876,1015,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">post mortem</emphasis>
. These bands are exclusive of chitons from this region (
<figureCitation box="[347,496,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1746,1770]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-18@35.[177,1411,181,1722]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 20. Chiton articulatus, specimen BL 27 mm, El Faro, Mazatlán (CNMO 5661); shows the tegmentum color details A, head valve; B, intermediate valves III-V; C, tail valve. Specimen BL 24.45 mm, Santa Elena, Oaxaca (CNMO 1066); shows color tegmentum details; D, head valve; E, detail of intermediate valves III-V; F, tail valve. Chaetopleura lurida, G, dorsal view of whole specimen BL 21.3 x 13.7 mm, Estacahuite, Oaxaca (CNMO 5813). Chaetopleura lurida, specimen of 27.9 x 15.4 mm, dorsal view of valve I and IV, Isla Partida, Baja California Sur (CNMO 1004), H, head valve and I, valve IV; J, whole specimen BL 25.8 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit; K, Ischnochiton muscarius, whole specimen BL 27.6 mm in dorsal view.Callistochiton elenensis, L, whole specimen BL 19.46 mm, La Paz, Baja California Sur (UAGRO 0060); M, detail of sculpturing of valves II-IV; N, Chiton articulatus, N, whole specimen in dorsal view, BL 37.2 mm, Sayulita, Nayarit (CNMO 40012)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691308" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691308/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">Figs. 20A–C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,151,646]" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. B. Sowerby I" authorityYear="1832" box="[199,406,223,249]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chitonidae" genus="Chiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="21" pageNumber="472" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="articulatus">
<emphasis box="[199,406,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">Chiton articulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most studied chiton species from 
<collectingCountry box="[877,963,223,249]" name="Mexico" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">México</collectingCountry>
(
